    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3333396619" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3333396619" />
    <a title="Urayoán" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/112803724-urayo-n"><img alt="Urayoán" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1637294394p2/112803724.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3333396619?book_show_action=true">Dec 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Urayoán" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Urayoán" href="/user/show/112803724-urayo-n">Urayoán</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3333396619" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15102282972272913325">Content Warning: ableism, conversion therapy, homophobia, nazism, abuse, ABA, Autism Speaks, and other potentially distressing topics.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/>.<br/><br/>Disgusting nightmare fuel for autistic readers. I couldn&apos;t even finish this book as, at no point along the many pages I read, did the book condemn the abusive and egotistical practices of what are now colloquially known in the internet as Autism Parents™, who describe autistic children as if &quot;possessed by demons&quot; because they don&apos;t like eye contact a</span>
  <span id="freeText15102282972272913325" style="display:none">Content Warning: ableism, conversion therapy, homophobia, nazism, abuse, ABA, Autism Speaks, and other potentially distressing topics.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br /><br />Disgusting nightmare fuel for autistic readers. I couldn't even finish this book as, at no point along the many pages I read, did the book condemn the abusive and egotistical practices of what are now colloquially known in the internet as Autism Parents™, who describe autistic children as if "possessed by demons" because they don't like eye contact and cry all night begging God to "cure" their child. I have zero sympathy for these people, but it is probably these people towards whom this book is directed. It is probably these people the reason why this book has such good reviews on Goodreads, and I have no interest in even amusing their views of self-described tragedy, going on and on incessantly about how their lives were ruined by their child. <br /><br />Beginning with a description of the discovery of autism spectrum disorder and, the now obsolete term, Asperger syndrome -obsolete because it is fundamentally ableist in attempts to separate what are called "high functioning" and "low functioning" autistics (the terms are ALSO ableist and outdated, and if you know anything about the autistic community is that they're also despised terms). The book goes into a lengthy description of the origins of the terms and the classifications while jumping over, oh so many, important details regarding Hans Asperger, like the fact that he was an active participant in the Nazi regime that worked to euthanize children with disabilities and "racial cleansing" programs to get rid of the "non-Aryans". An important topic which should be addressed if we're to understand where the idea of "high-functioning" (what was called Aspergers) and "low-functioning" (everything else in the spectrum). Hans' work was to find children who were "functional" (i.e., exploitable), everyone else was culturally expendable.<br /><br />Already off to a rocky start. What else is gonna happen? Well, for starters, the book takes no stance on the unempirical and disgusting malpractices of abusive parents seeking to "cure" their children, or their therapists, or their doctors, or anypne else which is a cog in the system that perpetuates the continuous pathologization, demonization, and blatant disregard for the self-autonomy of autistic people and their attempts at self-government over their bodies and lives. They're "not human", therefore all autonomy is stripped away from them before their eyes.<br /><br />Another important topic, ABA. Oh, how this one is such a doozy. This is ANOTHER topic on which the author merrily skips over the ugly details. Let's take Ivar Lovaas, the godfather of ABA therapy. Just to give an idea of the type of person involved in the mortifying conception of ABA, let's read his own words on the topic:<br /><br />“You see, you start pretty much from scratch when you work with an autistic child.  You have a person in the physical sense – they have hair, a nose and a mouth – but they are not people in the psychological sense.  One way to look at the job of helping autistic kids is to see it as a matter of constructing a person. You have the raw materials, but you have to build the person.”<br /><br />So, we have a founder who didn't even acknowledge autistic children as human beings. I wonder what other skeleton is hiding in the closet of this monster? How about his connections to what is now called conversion therapy? A practice that has been deemed illegal in many places, amounting to npthing else than "torturing the gay away." This is the person who we're dealing with, but none of this is discussed in the book (at least as far as I managed to read before giving up in a fit of repulsion and unequivocal rage). I won't even get into the controversy of some of the agencies which the author pointed at as sources of information and other resources during the writing if this book. The fact that no mention is made of Autism Speak's long history of abuse of members if the autism community is the most obvious case. and other agencies with similar histories are also mentioned in the same sentences.<br /><br />But what baffles me most of all about this book is how the author in some chapters goes on and on about the moments when he attended events organized by autistic people, for autistic people, to get a glimpse into the lives of autistic adults and to hear their side of the story. But apparently the author did not listen, or did not learn anything at all, cause after this we read about his interviews of autism parents who subjected their children to all forms of torture in attempts to "get the autism" out of their bodies. Maybe it was such dense confirmation bias that he discarded everything else aside from what served him when writing this horrendous book. <br /><br />This book is the perfect example of what happens when more voice is given to everyone else EXCEPT the marginalized group when speaking ABOUT said marginalized group itself. The people outside the group have ZERO business speaking for the marginalized group, dictating how the marginalized group should behave and live, and taking away the voices of said marginalized groups. To believe otherwise will always lead to abuse and tyranny against the marginalized groups. I can't even begin to describe the disgust, the anxiety, and the terror I felt while reading this damn book and the chapters in which parents cheerfully talk about their child as an animal which they hope to "train" via ABA as if teaching a dog to roll for treats. <br /><br />The only good part from all I read is probably the part where the book talks about the lives of Paul Dirac and Henry Cavendish, two scientists whose work and lives I deeply admire and respect, and whose work relates enormously to my current academic profession. The author speculates about the possibility that both scientists were autistic. Were they autistic? Possibly. I can certainly relate to some of their many traits and social interactions. Though, as always, the practice of diagnosing people from other time periods based on our present-day knowledge of medicine, biology, psychology, neuropsychology, etc. never leaves the realm of speculation. It might be the case, but we can never know for certain. As simpke as that, though a good case is made to indicate why the researchers believed this might've been the case. Ironically, I've gathered that this is the most disliked part of the book by some of neurotypical people that I've seen review it, maybe because it doesn't wallow in self-pitying tragedy porn and the rhetorical "heroic" storytelling of parents "sacrificing everything they love for their autistic child". The same cognitive disonance storytelling that they love to repeat themselves every day for that sweet, sweet confirmation bias they immensely love. That's what they picture autism as in popular media, and maybe that's why the chapters of succesful, potentially autistic scientists who got to where they were without an Autism Mom™ "sacrificing" her life to guarantee their child's success is so alien to them, and why some didn't care for that part.<br /><br />And even when I proclaim this to be the only part of the book I enjoyed, still, it is not without its fair share of criticism. That the author self-proclaims to know about autism from Rain Man -a movie which is NEVER a good source from which to base yourself on the topic- shows when discussing the aforementioned two world-famous scientists. The author apparently loves to fetishize autistic savants and their "miraculous" feats of the mind, and he goes on and on about how incredibly important they were to the world based on their contributions to society. Respecting autistic people under the expectation of exploiting their atypical minds under the hope of society attaining incredible accomplishments is as problematic a view as any of the aforementioned views described before. It negates the autistic community a right to self-autonomy, and can only make me think of the famous internet meme interpretation of the moral of Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer:<br /><br />"Deviation from cultural hegemony will be met with oppression and ostracization unless it can be exploited by the powerful for economic gain or social capital."<br /><br />Overall, it's no small cause for worry to know that this book is among the most read works on the topic of autism. It is absolutely terrifying to know that this is what neurotypicals are reading to "inform" themselves on autism, and I can only feel the deepest pain with the knowledge of so many autistic children suffering at the hands if ableist, egomaniacal parents hoping to "cure" their children's autism. I could keep going about so many other things, but I think I made my case. Imagine how much more material I could gather for my review if I had made it to the end of the book, but it's not worth the emotional distress that the book caused me.<br /><br />And for any autistic reader who reads this review: Turn away now, read anything else except for this. Read Cynthia Kim or any other actually autistic writer talking about the topic, but don't read this. Sincerely, an actually autistic adult who utterly despised this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15102282972272913325" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


