<div id="review_1355395839" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1355395839" />
    <a title="Jane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/288945-jane"><img alt="Jane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1547571834p2/288945.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1355395839?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jane" href="/user/show/288945-jane">Jane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/288945-jane?shelf=education">education</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/288945-jane?shelf=psychology">psychology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/288945-jane?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1355395839" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16192999868399633918">Some nonfiction books are groundbreaking. Some are engaging. This one is both. Using stories of historical figures, modern-day families, medical and psychological specialists, activists and autistic individuals, the book conveys the &quot;history&quot; of autism. What do we know? Is there really an epidemic? What works? Why is searching for a cure perhaps not the best strategy? Above all, though, it keeps the well-being of autistic children and adults at the center and in doing so raises tough questions a</span>
  <span id="freeText16192999868399633918" style="display:none">Some nonfiction books are groundbreaking. Some are engaging. This one is both. Using stories of historical figures, modern-day families, medical and psychological specialists, activists and autistic individuals, the book conveys the "history" of autism. What do we know? Is there really an epidemic? What works? Why is searching for a cure perhaps not the best strategy? Above all, though, it keeps the well-being of autistic children and adults at the center and in doing so raises tough questions and hard critique of how our society treats those who don't fit social norms. <br /><br />Thanks, NetGalley, for an advance copy in exchange for an honest review. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16192999868399633918" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


